descr:
Leopards (Panthera pardes) are the most beautiful of all the wild cats and the most elusive. Sighting one in the wild is a treat in itself let alone getting to photograph it in it's natural habitat.
The beautiful Double Cross female Leopard was elusive as usual but we did manage to sight her finally, early in the morning  coming out of the bushes going towards her resting place. 

Photographed on game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Elusive Beauty!

title: Mara Leopard 4269

descr:
The poor Warthog came strolling into the path of the Five Musketeers late in the evening. Although they were not interested in hunting the Warthog they chased him much further than he intended to go to rest for the night. 

The Five Musketeers is a new coalition of 5 cheetahs who have taken the Maasai Mara by storm and hunt much bigger prey than single cheetahs as there are  many more mouths to feed in the pride.
title: Run for your Life!

descr:
A rare sighting from the Mara as this is the first time I sighted it there, 

The Striated Heron (Butorides striata) also known as mangrove heron, little heron or green-backed heron, is a small heron, about 44 cm tall. Striated herons are mostly non-migratory and noted for some interesting behavioral traits. Their breeding habitat is small wetlands in the Old World tropics from west Africa to Japan and Australia, and in South America. 
Adults have a blue-grey back and wings, white underparts, a black cap, a dark line extends from the bill to under the eye and short yellow legs. Juveniles are browner above and streaked below.
These birds stand still at the water's edge and wait to ambush prey, but are easier to see than many small heron species. They mainly eat small fish, frogs and aquatic insects. They sometimes use bait, dropping a feather or leaf carefully on the water surface and picking fish that come to investigate.

This lovely Striated Heron was photographed late in the evening on the banks of the Talek River in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Golden Heron!

With the rest of the Ol Keju Pride feasting on a Wildebeest kill all afternoon the two males were no where to be sighted. 
As the sun began setting King of the Ol Keju pride came out into the open and sat there watching the setting sun. My colleagues were busy photographing the lovely sunset scene but I just couldn't get enough of the King.

Photographed on game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: King at Sunset!

descr:
The Lilac-breasted Roller (Coracias caudatus) is an African member of the roller family of birds. It is widely distributed in sub-Saharan Africa and the southern Arabian Peninsula, preferring open woodland and savanna; it is largely absent from treeless places. Usually found alone or in pairs, it perches conspicuously at the tops of trees, poles or other high vantage points from where it can spot insects, lizards, scorpions, snails, small birds and rodents moving about at ground level. Nesting takes place in a natural hole in a tree where a clutch of 2-4 eggs is laid, and incubated by both parents, who are extremely aggressive in defence of their nest, taking on raptors and other birds. During the breeding season the male will rise to great heights, descending in swoops and dives, while uttering harsh, discordant cries.
The sexes are alike in coloration. Juveniles do not have the long tail feathers that adults do.
This species is unofficially considered the national bird of Kenya. (Source: Wikipedia) 

This beautiful Lilac-breasted Roller was photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Beautiful Roller!

descr:
Malachite kingfishers (Corythornis cristatus) are typically seen near water, perched on reeds or branches over slow-moving water. After detecting its prey, it flies down to the water and catches it. It then returns to the perch and often beats the prey before it is swallowed, head first if it is a fish. While waiting for prey, the bird often bobs its head, raises and lowers its crest and flicks its tail. Perches are located 20-50 cm above the water, generally in areas of scattered vegetation with high fish density. This kingfisher is a diurnal bird and is usually solitary, apart from in the breeding season. Being a strongly territorial species, interactions between the owners and intruders may happen, involving threat displays, bill-grappling, flying attacks, and aerial chases. These birds are largely resident, seasonal movements being related to water levels. Juveniles disperse more widely than the adults. Their flight is rapid, and over water they usually fly low. 

This lovely Kingfisher was photographed near the Mara River in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Colourful Kingfisher!

descr:
As the sun began setting the King of the Ol Keju pride finally awoke after having been sleeping in the bushes all afternoon. He came out into the open and sat there watching the setting sun. 

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Awakening!

descr:
Rüppell's starling (Lamprotornis purpuroptera), also known as Rueppell's glossy-starling or Rueppell's long-tailed starling, is a species of starling in the family Sturnidae. It is found in Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Rwanda, Somalia, South Sudan, Sudan, Tanzania, and Uganda.

This lovely Starling was photographed foraging in the savannah plains of Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The White-eyed Starling!

descr:
Explored #5 2017-07-15

With the sun setting the King of the Ol Keju pride finally awoke and came out of the bushes as the temperature dropped from the days heat. The rest of the pride were nearby enjoying a wildebeest they had brought down in the afternoon. My colleagues were busy photographing the lovely sunset scene but I just couldn't get enough of the King.

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: King after Sunset!

descr:
Sitting there watching the Hippo crash wallowing in the water during the mid-day sun, a fight suddenly erupted with the resident male quickly put his challenger in his place by showing him his massive canines. 
Hippos mark their territory by defecation. While depositing the faeces, hippos spin their tails to distribute their excrement over a greater area. "Yawning" serves as a threat display. When fighting, male hippos use their incisors to block each other's attacks and their large canines to inflict injuries. When hippos become over-populated or a habitat is reduced, bulls sometimes attempt infanticide, but this behaviour is not common under normal conditions. Incidents of hippo cannibalism have been documented, but this is believed to be the behaviour of distressed or sick hippos.

The common hippopotamus (Hippopotamus amphibius) was photographed in the Mara River in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Battle of the Giants!

descr:
Best shots of this trip to the Masai Mara - 
SCARFACE, very large bruised and scared male lion  found between the Talek and Ol Keju Ronkai rivers, back to back with his brother Morani. Scarface is on of the sons of Notch and one of the most important lions in the Masai Mara. He is the leader or one of the leaders of the Marsh Pride and was found here with his brother Morani in the former territory of his other brother Long-face. Long-face had been driven off by Loki and the three other Vikings, a new group of four blond 4 year old male lions.  Scarface looks like his Disney character Scar; but is in fact one of the most stabilising forces in the Masai Mara NR (less so on the Triangle side of the Mara River, where he frequently goes for "relations") and is well know for being the most aggressive fighter around.  So no doubt he and his brother heard the new lions calling/roaring and came for a look. He and his brother's roars were so frightening to the young interlopers, that the Vikings ran away when Scarface and his brother showed up.

This is the final processed version for now and optimised for web viewing.

descr:
This is Scarface a 9 year old and perhaps the most impressive lion in the Masai Mara. He and is 3 male brothers are all sons of Notch who work in coalition and called The Musketeers. We found him and his equally large brother Morani close to where we found the 4 new young males that had taken over control of the area south of the Ol Keju Ronkai river and north of Lookout.
Scarface and the Musketeers became know as the Marsh Pride when they took control in 2012. Since then Scarface has been found most often on both sides of the Mara River near Main Crossing. The fact he is now on the Southside of the Ol Keju Ronkai river is interesting and possibly linked to the rise of the 4 Vikings (4 year old males). The storey unfolds over the next images.

descr: Cattle are source of food for the Maasai.  They must be carefully tended and escorted to feeding grounds daily and returned each evening.  Lions frequent the area and cattle present an opportunistic meal, thus a close vigil is required.
title: Young Maasai tending cattle on escarpment overlooking Maasai Mara

descr:
The formidable African fish eagle (Haliaeetus vocifer) is a large species of eagle that is found throughout sub-Saharan Africa wherever large bodies of open water occur that have an abundant food supply. 
The African fish eagle feeds mainly on fish, which it swoops down upon from a perch in a tree, snatching the prey from the water with its large, clawed talons. The eagle then flies back to its perch to eat its catch.

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Flying Fisher!

descr: This photo, unfortunately, contains a non-trivial fraction of the Black Rhino population. We were told that there are only six in the park (and about 5000 in the world - source WWF.) The horn of the other rhino was removed to discourage poachers, which has apparently not been too successful, and the practice has been discontinued.
title: Black Rhinoceros

descr:
The King of the Ol Keju pride finally awoke after having been sleeping in the bushes all afternoon. As the sun began setting he came out into the open and sat there watching the setting sun. My colleagues were busy photographing the lovely sunset scene but I just couldn't get enough of the King.

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: King at Sunset!

descr: I was lucky to catch this lioness's gaze as she enjoyed some refreshing water on a warm day on the Mara last month. One of 25,000+ images I'm trying to process from my trip! Masai Mara, Kenya Jeff My Website ¦ My Blog ¦ Google+¦ Facebook
title: "Those Eyes"

descr:
Cheetahs (Acinonyx jubatus) have a very high High mortality rates according to a research done in the Serengeti. In a 1994 study, nearly 77% of litters died before eight weeks of birth, and nearly 83% of those alive could not make it to adolescence (14 weeks). Lions emerged as the major predator of juveniles, accounting for nearly 78% of the deaths. The study concluded that the survival rate of cubs till weaning was a mere 4.8%. This was attributed to the open terrain of the region, which does not allow cheetahs to conceal themselves. Cheetah cubs face higher mortality than most other large mammals.

Malaika & her Cubs were photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Super Mommy!

descr:
One of the mature females of the Marsh Pride is seen overlooking the Savannah plains early in the morning praying for a successive hunt to feed the huge resident pride. 

Photographed in the Marsh Area of the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: Queen of the Marsh!

descr:
I recently spent two full weeks in Kenya on a photo safari and came home with a frightening number of images.

Of all those shots, this one may be my favorite. A group of cheetahs were drinking at the Mara river.  I caught this moment as one of them seemed to be considering her own reflection before lapping up that first drink of water.

Moments like this will stay with me until I leave this earth.

Jeff
title: "Mirror, Mirror..."

descr: The oribi is a small, slender antelope; it reaches nearly 50–67 centimetres (20–26 in) at the shoulder and weighs 12–22 kilograms (26–49 lb). The head-and-body length is typically between 92 and 110 centimetres (36 and 43 in).  The oribi is diurnal (active mainly during the day), though some activity may also be observed at night.[12] The animal rests in cover during rain events.  Primarily a grazer, the oribi prefers fresh grasses and browses occasionally. Grasses can constitute up to 90% of the diet.
title: Oribi, Maasai Mara

descr: The Maasai are indigenous people.  Here we visit their village and join them in a welcome dance.  Both the men and women carve the ear in an extreme fashion of accomodate hanging of multiple pieces of jewelry.  This process starts at an early age.  The lobe droops with age after years of gravity pulling it downward.

descr: The Maasai lion or East African lion (Panthera leo nubica syn. Panthera leo massaica) is a lion subspecies that is found in eastern Africa. The type specimen is described as being from "Nubia". The subspecies includes previously recognized subspecies like massaica, which was initially described from the Tanganyika Territory in Eastern Africa.  They typically inhabit savanna and grassland, although they may take to bush and forest. Lions are unusually social compared to other cats. descr:
This giraffe has spent about 30 minutes just safely positioning to get a drink.  3 lions are sleeping just 50 yards in the direction he is looking.    After all the caution, he took exactly two quick gulps of water and then moved away.  After he grabs a quick gulp, because of his vulnerable position with danger nearby, he snaps his head back up erect so quickly that water and saliva fly everywhere, which is shown clearly in this photo.  If you zoom in, you'll see the water show and the saliva trails frozen by the high shutter speed.

The giraffe (Giraffa) is a genus of African even-toed ungulate mammals, the tallest living terrestrial animals and the largest ruminants. The genus consists of eleven species including Giraffa camelopardalis, the type species. Seven of these species are extinct, prehistoric species known from fossils, while four are still extant. Whereas Giraffa once was thought to contain a single extant species with numerous subspecies, research into the mitochondrial and nuclear DNA of Giraffa has revealed four to six distinct extant species. The four-species taxonomic classification has the genus Giraffa composed of the species Giraffa giraffa (southern giraffe), Giraffa tippelskirchi (Masai giraffe), Giraffa reticulata (reticulated giraffe) and Giraffa camelopardalis (northern giraffe).
title: Maasai Giraffe Sprays Water After Taking a Drink

descr: The plains zebra (Equus quagga, formerly Equus burchellii), also known as the common zebra or Burchell's zebra, or locally as the "quagga"[3] (not to be confused with the extinct subspecies), is the most common and geographically widespread species of zebra.[4] It ranges from the south of Ethiopia through East Africa to as far south as Botswana and eastern South Africa. descr:
You wouldn't believe the hippo is one of the most aggressive animals in the world looking at this group. We came across 30 or so individuals in the Mara River on the Masai Mara National Reserve, Kenya. They were all pretty comatose. 

The word "hippopotamus" is derived from the ancient Greek,  from  hippos, "horse", and  potamos, "river", meaning "horse of the river". In English, the plural is hippopotamuses, but "hippopotami" is also used; "hippos" can be used as a short plural. Hippopotamuses are gregarious, living in groups of up to thirty animals. A group is called a pod, herd, dale, or bloat.

Studying the interaction of male and female hippopotamuses has long been complicated because females and young males are almost indistinguishable in the field. Although hippos lie close to each other, they do not seem to form social bonds except between mothers and daughters; they are not social animals. The reason they huddle close together is unknown. 

Hippopotamuses are territorial only in water, where a bull presides over a small stretch of river, on average 250 m (270 yd) in length, and containing 10 females. The largest pods can contain over 100 hippos. Younger bachelors are allowed in a bull's stretch, as long as they behave submissively toward the bull. The territories of hippos exist to establish mating rights. Within the pods, the hippos tend to segregate by gender. Bachelors lounge near other bachelors, females with other females, and the bull on his own. When hippos emerge from the water to graze, they do so individually.

Hippopotamuses appear to communicate vocally, through grunts and bellows, and they may practice echolocation, but the purpose of these vocalizations is currently unknown. Hippos have the unique ability to hold their heads partially above the water and send out a cry that travels through both water and air; individuals respond above and under water.

descr:
The stunning beauty, Grey Crowned Crested Crane posing very well for it's portrait breaking its busy feeding schedule.
These cranes are omnivores, eating plants, seeds, grain, insects, frogs, worms, snakes, small fish and the eggs of aquatic animals. Stamping their feet as they walk, they flush out insects which are quickly caught and eaten. The birds also associate with grazing herbivores, benefiting from the ability to grab prey items disturbed by antelopes and gazelles. They spend their entire day looking for food. At night, the crowned crane spends its time in the trees sleeping and resting.
Photographed in the Mara Triangle, Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.

descr:
The beautiful little bee-eater (Merops pusillus) is an abundant and tame bird, familiar throughout its range. There have been estimated to be between 60-80 million little bee-eaters. 
It breeds in open country with bushes, preferably near water. Just as the name suggests, bee-eaters predominantly eat insects, especially bees, wasps and hornets, which are caught in the air by sorties from an open perch.  

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: Mr & Mrs B!

descr: A leopard rests in an acacia.  The life of a cat in Africa seems to consist of very long bouts of rest and sleep, punctuated by intense moments of feeding and violence.  Image captured in the Masai Mara Park in Kenya using a Canon 7D and 100-400 mm lens (at 400mm); 1/125 sec., f/5.6, ISO 800.
title: Lazy day

descr: An adolescent leopard sits in an acacia with the Thomson's gazelle that (presumably) its mother captured for their feast.  When we first arrived at this tree in the morning the gazelle was unattended, but the young leopard arrived later in the afternoon.  We were told that it was joined by its mother the next morning, though we did not see it.  Image captured in the Masai Mara Park, Kenya, using a Canon 7D and 100-400 mm lens (at 182mm) 1/640 sec., f/5.0, ISO 800.
title: Gazelle repast

descr: A spotted hyaena's ominous yawn shows its strong jaws.  Image captured in the Masai Mara, Kenya using a Canon 7D and 100-400mm lens (at 271mm); 1/500 sec., f/5.6, ISO 800.
title: Jaws

descr: Zebras stand beneath the shade of the trees at the edge of the Masai Mara Park in Kenya.  The alignment of the animals and their stripes creates a sense of group identity and community that I love. Image caputred using a Canon 7D and 100-400 mm lens (at 400mm); 1/500 sec., f/5.6, ISO 400.
title: A dazzle of zebras

descr:
On our way back to Elephant Pepper Camp in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya, we spotted a grassland pipit sitting upon a rock, soaking in the warmth of the morning sun.

We stopped to photograph this little creature in the beautiful light, where I captured this view of the pipit posing and surveying the surroundings.

descr:
Sitting in the wild watching these beautiful gentle giants going about their daily routine you will suddenly sight a sudden confrontation amongst the youngsters. 
Each and every one is trying to emphasise their seniority in age over the youngsters and setting there pecking order in the herd. 
Photographed in the Mara Triangle, Transmara, Kenya.

descr:
On day 10 in the Mara North Conservancy, we spent the afternoon and evening with a pair of mating leopards, which is an incredible and rare sight.

In this image, the young leopardess rests in the thick grass in between intense mating sessions, while the much larger and older male leopard lingers nearby before his next approach.
title: Resting Leopardess

descr:
Our 11th game drive in the Mara North Conservancy was spent in a spectacular and uncommon fashion.

After a visit to a Maasai village not far from camp, we headed out and encountered a pair of mating leopards!

Here, the male, having spotted the female resting up in the tree, attempts to climb.  Shortly afterwards, the female descended and there were many explosive mating sessions as we watched in awe and took in the dramatic sound of a leopard growling during mating.
title: Amourous Climber

title: Black-Bellied Bustard

descr:
This is Baba, a Maasai tribesman who lives in the Mara North Conservancy in south-western Kenya.

On our sixth day in the Mara, we headed out into the plains, not far from camp, where we spent some time photographing Baba against the rising sun, and later in the morning golden hour.

Here, Baba is depicted in traditional Maasai consume, complete with spear.
title: The Maasai

descr: After an intense afternoon in which a Cheli Pride lioness roared and anxiously waited for her cubs and fellow lionesses to return to her, while enduring the constant pestering of flies and a heavy downpour of rain from an afternoon thunderstorm, at long last, the Cheli Pride is reunited in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya.
title: Reunited

descr:
A nice spot to park a vehicle when out and about on the plains of Kenya's Mara North Conservancy.

Pictured nearby is Mario's Tree, a solitary, photogenic acacia tree, set against a stunning sunrise.
title: Great Parking Spot

descr: One of the cubs from the Mara North Conservancy's resident Cheli Pride sits satisfied, looking into the distance, after a fantastic afternoon sighting of the pride members gorging themselves on a zebra kill nearby.
title: Satisfied Cheli Cub
Storm clouds gathering at sunset. I don't know how we'll pitch our tents as it's already started drizzling.   #MasaiMara #Migration2015 #Onetouch_Mara #TembeaKenya #XperiaZ1

descr:
On our final game drive in the Maasai Mara, we encountered a pod of hippos in the water.

This hippo watched us closely (and we were close) and made sure to let us know that he is the master of his domain.
title: Master of My Domain

descr: A juvenile martial eagle surveys his territory and looks for signs of opportunity from his high perch in the Mara North Conservancy of south-western Kenya.
title: Juvenile Martial Eagle

descr:
On the morning after we witnessed the Cheli Pride feasting on a zebra kill, we returned to the kill site to see if there was anything left, or any activity.

A hyena or two had been on the scene, and this fellow, by now in the distance, had grabbed a piece of what little was left, and trotted off into the plains a little further away.

While the predation of an animal is nature's way in the wilderness, and at times difficult to watch or accept, nothing goes to waste, and one animal's demise represents the continued survival of other species.  It is a fine balance, but it works.
title: Hyena on the Lookout

descr: A beautiful crimson, cloud-laden sky greeted us as we began our fourth day in the Mara North Conservancy at a favourite solitary acacia tree known as "Mario's Tree".
title: Crimson Mara

descr: During an intense sighting of the Cheli Pride feasting on a zebra kill, this cute little cub -- one of the younger members of the pride -- was very engaged in the business of chowing down, and kept feeding well after the other lions had all moved aside to rest and roll around.
title: Chowing Down

descr:
One morning after a bush breakfast with other guests of Elephant Pepper Camp, we headed towards the Mara River, which we didn't quite reach due to our discovery of a River Pride lioness up a tree.

Lions aren't great climbers, and this lioness seemed to be stuck in the bough, awkwardly repositioning herself every now and then, and seemingly attempting to descend.

Here, she looks rather uncomfortable, but in spite of her challenging predicament, seeing a lioness in a tree is rather uncommon, and was a special, unexpected treat on day 3 in the Mara.
title: A Little Bit Stuck

descr:
After spending some time watching the Cheli Pride feasting on a zebra kill, this big tusker, and many members of the herd, approached the area where we were positioned.

The elephants had been in distress as they realised a pride of lions was within close proximity, and much trumpeting and running was to be heard and seen; but soon enough, the elephants relaxed and continued grazing.
title: Big Tusker

descr:
One of the many cubs of the Cheli Pride decided to have a drink from a small watering hole after the pride feasted on a zebra kill late in the afternoon in the Mara North Conservancy.

This little cub seemed as interesting in looking at me as I was in looking at him.
title: Cub Drool

descr:
On a morning game drive in the Maasai Mara, we encountered a breeding herd of Cape buffalo.

Here, a mother and calf graze together under an overcast sky while the other members of the heard rest, groom and graze in the background.
title: Mother and Calf

descr:
When we headed out into the Mara plains in the afternoon, we quickly encountered a few grazing elephants.

Unusually for my style, I shot a wider image to capture not only the elephants, but the plains and the moody sky under which they were grazing.

The sky was develop into a dramatic show later in the afternoon and into the early evening.
title: Ellies Under a Moody Sky

descr:
During a fantastic sighting of the River Pride of lions near the Mara River in the Mara North Conservancy, we encountered a female and two young male lions.

This young male, his youth apparent by the length of his developing mane, wandered over and sat under the shade of a large tree as the heat of the morning intensified.
title: River Pride Male

descr:
On our third day in the Mara North Conservancy, we headed towards the Mara River, where we encountered an unusual sighting of a lioness in a tree.

Unlike leopards, lions aren't particularly good at climbing, and this lioness, from the River Pride, spent a fair bit time awkwardly positioned in a bough in the tree.
title: Lioness in a Tree
Crocodile right before he grabbed and killed wildebeest! #migration #crossingtheriver #kenya #safari #travel #africa
And this is how wildebeests fly! #migration #crossingtheriver #safari #maasaimara #kenya #africa #travel

descr: A Cape buffalo, looking less than amused, during a sighting in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya.
title: I am Not Amused

descr:
On our fourth day in the Maasai Mara region of south-west Kenya, we headed out early to photograph an acacia tree at sunrise.

On this particular morning we were greeted with some pleasing conditions, and in the very few seconds left before the sun peeked over the horizon, I captured this image of an iconic acacia tree on the Mara plains.

A topi can also be seen on the plains, grazing and awaiting the warmth of the rising sun.
title: Thirty Seconds Before Sunrise

descr: A portrait of Maasai tribesman Baba looking over the plains as the warm light of golden hour shines upon him at the beginning of another fantastic day in the Mara North Conservancy.
title: Contemplation

descr:
A magnificent time was had with the two Cheli Pride brothers at Leopard Gorge on our second night in the Mara.

Initially one of the Cheli brothers was spotted near the top of the gorge, and shortly later, he was joined by his brother.

In this image, the lion had made his way to a distant tree for a manicure.  He soon returned and joined his brother for some bonding and lazing around before the night's hunting began.
title: Scratching Post

descr:
On our second evening in the Mara, we encountered two magnificent male lions -- brothers in the Cheli Pride.

Here, one of the Cheli brothers heads back toward us to join his brother for some bonding and lazing before later preparing for the serious business of being a male lion in the Mara wilderness.
title: On Approach

descr: On a morning game drive on our second day in the Mara North Conservancy, we encountered a lone African white-backed vulture perched high up in a tree, vigilantly surveying its surroundings and looking for opportunities to scavenge food from other predators.
title: Vulture Vigilance

descr:
On an afternoon game drive in the Mara North Conservancy, we encountered the Cheli Pride feasting on a zebra it had killed earlier in the day.

Here, after feeding time as the cubs were playing and the mothers were resting, this lioness posed regally as she observed her surroundings.
title: Cheli Pride Lioness

descr: A view of a lone acacia tree, affectionately known as Mario's Tree, on the plains of the Mara North Conservancy in south-west Kenya, during a dawn which greeted us with a stunning sky.
title: Lone Acacia

descr: A full view of a grey crowned crane surveying the Mara plains of Kenya from an elevated position on a log.
title: Crowning Around

descr: On our second day in the Mara North Conservancy, after shooting an acacia tree against a dramatic morning sky, we soon encountered the Cheli Pride again, where I shot a few images of this cute cub.
title: Cuteness Factor

descr:
This eland was resting on the grass in the Mara North Conservancy during a morning game drive.

We didn't encounter many elands during our time in the Mara, but we spotted a few, and in this case stopped to capture a few images.
title: Eland at Rest

descr:
One of the Cheli Pride lionesses was sitting in the grass on her own when we encountered her one afternoon.

Here she is, roaring for the rest of her pride to join her, as a rainstorm descends upon the Mara.
title: Roaring in the Rain

descr:
An encounter with a young male leopard in the Mara North Conservancy was a special occasion, as it was our first sighting of an elusive animal and our first time seeing a leopard in a tree.

It took place at Leopard Gorge towards the western side of the conservancy.

It was a short-lived sighting, as he soon disappeared into the foliage, and photography was more or less over after this shot.
title: Leopard in a Tree

descr:
This image of a lioness was shot during one of our first game drives in the Mara North Conservancy in southern Kenya, not far from the Tanzania border.

During this sighting, one of the adult females from the Cheli Pride was basking in the afternoon sun with her cub.  The rest of the pride wasn't visible, but couldn't have been too far away.
title: Lioness on the Savannah

descr:
The Maasai Mara provided us with some fantastic opportunities to photograph birds in good light and from good distances.

Here on a morning game drive during our fourth day in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya, we encountered a grassland pipit on our way back to camp, and I was fortunate enough to capture his profile before he flew away.
title: Grassland Pipit

descr: Baba, a Maasai tribesman, stands on the plains of the Mara North Conservancy as a new day in the East African wilderness is greeted by the rising sun.
title: Maasai at Sunrise

descr:
During our second game drive in the Mara North Conservancy, we had four separate elephant sightings.

Here, in the distance, a young adult from a breeding herd is grazing on the open plains, while the other elephants in the herd are nearby.
title: Giant Grazer

descr:
After shooting some silhouette images of an acacia tree during a fantastic sunrise, we were lucky enough to spot a few jackals in the morning light.

Jackals can be very difficult to photograph, as they're constantly in the move.  In this case I was lucky enough to have the jackal stop for long enough to capture a portrait.
title: The Jackal

descr:
To my surprise, many of my best wildlife images during our Maasai Mara safari depicted birds.

I'm traditionally not a bird photographer, preferring, both in personality and in a visual sense, the big cats of Africa; but I landed quite a few pleasing images of birds during the trip.

This is a pied kingfisher, which we spotted rapidly ascending and descending in one spot.

By sheer luck, I managed to land a crisp shot of the kingfisher in flight.

Photographing birds in flight -- particularly small birds -- takes a lot of skill and luck, and in my case, it was more luck than skill.
title: Suspended

descr: A Maasai tribesman in traditional dress, armed with his spear, looks towards the rising sun from the solitude of the savannah in the Mara North Conservancy in Kenya.
title: Staring at the Sun

descr:
On a number of a occasions during our wildlife and landscape photography safari in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya, we stopped at an iconic acacia tree, known affectionately as Mario's tree, as our friend and safari leader Mario often photographs this tree.

On this particular occasion we were greeted with a nice dawn sky, so I got down on a low angle and shot Mario's tree against the dramatic reds and blues in the distant sky.
title: Mario's Tree

descr:
On our final game drive in the Mara North Conservancy, we happened upon a dik-dik under a small tree.

I was fortunate enough to fire off a shot of him looking straight at me before he scurried off into the scrub.
title: Dik-Dik

descr:
During a terrific sighting of the Cheli Pride during an afternoon game drive in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya, an almighty rain storm descended upon us.

This female lion from the pride had been sitting in the open, roaring for the rest of her pride to join her.  This made conditions great for photography!

Before the other lions emerged from the distance, it had rained, and here, I managed to capture the lioness shaking the excess water from her face.
title: Shake It Off

descr:
On a morning game drive in the Mara North Conservancy, we encountered a black-bellied bustard sitting on a small mound close to the side of the track, so we stopped to capture the bustard in the warm light.

We watched and photographed it for a while, studying the calling patterns of the bird, and then when we were familiar with the behavioural pattern, we fired off a rapid series of shots to capture its call.

Here in this image, I have captured the bustard at full neck extension during its call.
title: The Bustard Can Sing

descr:
On our fifth day in the Maasai Mara, we decided to head out of Mara North Conservancy and into the publicly-accessible Maasai Mara National Reserve, where we would later find cheetahs.

Earlier on the morning game drive, we happened across a mother giraffe with her calf. Both were nicely positioned on the horizon, so we shot silhouettes of the giraffes on the plains as the morning sun's rays shone upon them.
title: Wait for Me, Mum!

descr:
This is Elephant Pepper Camp in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya.

At EPC dinners are communal, and mornings and early evenings often see people assemble around the camp fire for a hot drink and a chat.
title: Around the Camp Fire

descr:
During one of our encounters with a herd of buffalo, I was fortunate enough to isolate one of the animals in a photographically pleasing pose, but also capture an oxpecker launching into flight from the top of the buffalo's head.

I didn't realise I even captured this until I reviewed the images days after capturing them.
title: Lift Off

descr:
On our final afternoon/evening game drive in the Mara North Conservancy in Kenya, we encountered a pair of mating leopards.

We spent quite a while with them as they mated, rested, mated again, and continued the cycle.

Here in this image, the male, who I have called Big Boy, is resting after a swift and ferocious mating session with the female nearby.

Leopards are notoriously elusive and difficult to find, and to have found two and witnessed them mating was an incredible experience.
title: Big Boy

descr:
Early this morning, we headed out for a day-long game drive, stopping at a place called "Mario's Tree", which we have photographed at sunrise twice before.

This time we decided to shoot a silhouette to capture the essence of a safari, including our people (except me; I was behind the camera), 4WD and an acacia tree on the Mara plains, all set against a magical African sunrise.
title: On Safari

descr:
During this afternoon's game drive, we experienced an amazing lion sighting, in which this Cheli Pride mother, on her own, sat on a mound in the open, roaring for the rest of her pride to join her.

Thunderstorms were brewing nearby, and soon enough the rain started falling.

After a while longer, the lioness departed in search for the pride, which she found, with us in hot pursuit.
title: Cheli Mother
P1030511Allans photo of hipos on the banks of the Mara River Kenya spot a croc too

descr:
On our second day in the Mara North Conservancy, we encountered a young male leopard at a spectacular location called, aptly enough, Leopard Gorge.

I captured this image during the early part of our sighting, soon after which, he disappeared into the foliage and was never easy to photograph again.

The conditions were difficult, the light was lacking, the focal length was long and the foliage was dense, and by all accounts, I captured the only decent leopard image of the day, hence the title.

I hope my viewers enjoy this rare glimpse of an elusive leopard in his natural habitat.
title: Leopard of the Day

descr:
This experienced male lion from the Cheli Pride was the first male lion we encountered on our wildlife safari in the Maasai Mara.

We found him at a fantastic location called Leopard Gorge.

He was sitting up on the plateau, surveying his territory in the late afternoon.

Not long afterwards, his brother emerged from the distance and the two brothers engaged in bonding and resting.
title: Surveying

descr:
On our first early morning game drive in the Mara North Conservancy, we were greeted with a moody sky, which had earlier delivered rain.

Before heading further into the plains in search of lions (which we found), we stopped to shoot an iconic acacia tree against a moody sky on the Mara plains.
title: The Moody Mara Plains

descr:
Here we are, on our first day of an amazing wildlife photography safari in Kenya.

This is a view of our tent (the honeymoon tent) at Elephant Pepper Camp in the Mara North Conservancy of Kenya.
title: Elephant Pepper Camp's Honeymoon Tent

descr:
Africa’s most common large vulture, the white-backed vulture (Gyps africanus) is an accomplished scavenger that feeds on the carcasses of Africa’s large animals. Its plumage is dark brown with black skin on the neck and head, making the white lower-back, for which it is named, even more prominent. The white-backed vulture has black eyes and a strong, slightly hooked black bill, contrasting with its pale crown and hindneck. 
White-backed vultures are scavengers, feeding on the soft muscle, organ tissue and bone fragments of large carcasses. With their large, broad wings they can soar and circle for hours as they search for carrion. Their excellent eyesight enables them to spot food from high in the air, and they also keep an eye on other vultures, quickly following if they see another making a sudden descent. Up to 200 white-backed vultures can gather at a carcass; an enormous elephant carcass may even attract a thousand. With so many birds trying to feed, fights are inevitable. Accompanied with grunts and goose-like hisses and cackles, the scrum of vultures can be seen inserting their long, bare necks under the skin of the carcass or crawling into the ribcage as they feed on the dead remains. After gorging themselves, the vultures may bathe together with other species at a favourite site, or rest with their wings spread and backs to the sun.

This white-backed vulture was photographed on a early morning game drive in the savannah plains of Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Accomplished Scavenger!

descr:
The saddle-billed stork (Ephippiorhynchus senegalensis) is a large wading bird in the stork family, Ciconiidae. It is a widespread species which is a resident breeder in sub-Saharan Africa. 
The stork's body is completely white with a featherless red patch of skin in the center of the breast, but the color darkens during the breeding season.
The head, neck, and the tail feathers are also black but have a green iridescence. Primary and secondary flight feathers (the longer and broader feathers on the trailing side of the wing) are white, with black upper and lower covert feathers (smaller, shorter feathers covering the base of the secondary and primary feathers).
The beak is red with a black band going around the middle, and on the upper side is the yellow “saddle” that includes small wattles that hang below the underside of the beak at the base that look like stirrups. The legs are black with red bands around the joints and on their feet. 
Even though the female storks are 10-15% smaller than the males, the way you can tell them apart is that the females have yellow eyes and the males have dark brown eyes.

This beautiful female Saddle-billed Stork was photographed on a late evening game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Beautiful Female!

descr:
Distinguished by its exceptionally beautiful, black-spotted coat, the Leopard (Panthera pardus) is also recognised for its supreme stealth and its remarkable versatility. Despite being the smallest of the ‘big cats’, the leopard is the most widespread of all wild cat species, and is well known for the variety of prey it takes, as well as its ability to occupy a range of habitats, from deserts and mountains to jungles and swamps.
The leopard can be individually identified by its spot pattern. Its distinctive black spots contrast with the pale background coat colour and the white underparts. Small, solid black spots mark the head, throat, chest and lower limbs, with larger black patches on the belly. The leopard’s back, flanks and upper limbs are patterned with pale-centred rosettes, which vary greatly in shape and size. 
A superb predator, the leopard has a long, well-muscled body, thick, short limbs, and broad, powerful paws. Its powerful jaws enable it to kill and dismember prey, while particularly long, sensitive whiskers allow the leopard to ‘feel’ its way as it hunts at night. Several long hairs in the eyebrows help protect the eyes from vegetation as it moves through the undergrowth. The leopard is also an extremely agile climber, with heavily-muscled shoulders and forelimbs which aid it in climbing, pinning down prey and hauling prey into trees.

Photographed on an early morning game drive in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Spotted Beauty!

descr:
The wood sandpiper (Tringa glareola) is a small wader. This Eurasian species is the smallest of the shanks, which are mid-sized long-legged waders of the family Scolopacidae. The genus name Tringa is the New Latin name given to the green sandpiper by Aldrovandus in 1599 based on Ancient Greek trungas, a thrush-sized, white-rumped, tail-bobbing wading bird mentioned by Aristotle. The specific glareola is from Latin glarea, " gravel".

descr:
Thomson's gazelle (Eudorcas thomsonii) is one of the best-known gazelles and is sometimes referred to as a "tommy". Thomson's gazelles can be found in numbers exceeding 550,000 in Africa and are recognised as the most common type of gazelle in East Africa. The Thomson's gazelle can reach speeds of 80-90 km/h. It is the fifth-fastest land animal, after the cheetah, its main predator. 

Thomson’s Gazelles have slender legs and a short, black tail which is constantly in motion swinging back and forth like a window blade wiper. They have large ears and eyes and a narrow muzzle. Their heads are small and they have a lightweight body which enables them to run fast and make sharp turns. To make up for their vulnerability out on the plains, gazelles have an excellent sense of hearing which makes them exceptionally alert to sounds. They also have excellent smell and sight which is their main source of communicating with each other.

Photographed on a late evening game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Handsome Tommy!

descr:
This beautiful Cheetah got lucky and managed to chase down successfully a young Thompson's Gazelle (Tommy) early in the morning. descr:
The common eland (Taurotragus oryx), also known as the southern eland or eland antelope, is a savannah and plains antelope found in East and Southern Africa. It is a species of the family Bovidae and genus Taurotragus. 
The common eland is one of the largest antelopes in existence. Its coat is tan, fawn or tawny coloured, turning slightly bluish-grey on the neck and shoulders with age, and a short dark mane runs down the back of the neck. Both male and female common eland possess horns that rise with a slight twist, back from the head to sharp points. The horns of the male are more robust and bear more distinct ridges than those of the female. The massive adult males can also be recognised by the large fold of loose skin that hangs below the throat (the dewlap), and the patch of long, coarse, dark hair on the forehead. These features become respectively larger and bushier with age. The common eland has a fairly small and pointed mouth and muzzle, small, narrow ears, and a long tail with a tuft of black hair at the tip. 
Elands are widely hunted and this hunting pressure, in combination with habitat loss, has led to their disappearance from much of their former range, although Common Elands are still widely distributed and well represented in national parks and are even semi-domesticated as exotics in several countries.

Photographed on a late evening game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Mighty Antelope!

descr:
The cheetah is the fastest land animal in the world. They can reach a top speed of around 113 km per hour. A cheetah can accelerate from 0 to 113 km in just a few seconds. Cheetahs are extremely fast however they tire quickly and can only keep up their top speed for a few minutes before they are too tired to continue.
One way to always recognise a cheetah is by the long, black lines which run from the inside of each eye to the mouth. These are usually called “tear lines” and scientists believe they help protect the cheetah’s eyes from the harsh sun and help them to see long distances.
Cheetahs are the only big cat that cannot roar. They can purr though and usually purr most loudly when they are grooming or sitting near other cheetahs.
While lions and leopards usually do their hunting at night, cheetahs hunt for food during the day.
A cheetah has amazing eyesight during the day and can spot prey from 5 km away.
With their light body weight and blunt claws, cheetahs are not well designed to protect themselves or their prey. When a larger or more aggressive animal approaches a cheetah in the wild, it will give up its catch to avoid a fight.
Cheetahs only need to drink once every three to four days.

Photographed on a late evening game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Poser!

descr:
The Water Thick-knee (Burhinus vermiculatus), or water dikkop is a species of bird in the family Burhinidae.
The water thick-knee is an African terrestrial wader in the stone-curlew/thick-knee family. It grows to a length of 38 - 41 cm. It is a cryptically colored bird which makes for good camouflage. Like other birds in the family it has large yellow eyes, a short, stout bill and knee joints that are larger than in species of other related families. 
Like other thick-knee species, the water thick-knee is mainly nocturnal and will normally rest close to water during the day hidden away in vegetation or amongst rocks. It is somewhat less nocturnal than other thick-knee species making sightings more likely during daytime hours. As the name suggests, it prefer habitats close to water, such as shorelines, riverbanks, mangroves, and other forms of sheltered wetland. At night it will forage alone, in pairs, or in small groups for invertebrates and smaller vertebrates such as reptiles and frogs. It rarely ventures further than 1 km from water.

This beautiful Water Thick-knee is a lifer and was photographed on a late evening game drive in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Thick Knee!

descr: Su plumaje es principalmente de color pardo grisáceo, con las plumas de vuelo de alas y cola negras al igual que su garganta. Presenta una gran mancha blanca en la parte frontal del píleo con un marco negruzco; el resto de su cabeza y cuello están veteados en negro. Se caracteriza por tener una carúncula colgante, amarilla con el borde superior rojo, a ambos lados de la base del pico, que también es amarillo con la punta negra, y también son amarillas sus largas patas. Su obispillo es blanco. En vuelo también se puede observar una lista blanca en las alas entre las plumas negras y las pardas, en la parte superior. También son blancas las coberteras de la parte inferior de las alas.

descr: Such a sight to see--- this leopard was in a tree with its kill, having its dinner. The raw power of the cat, and the sheer beauty of his grace and strength were a sight to behold. We watched in awe for nearly an hour as it dined rather obscured by the leafy branches, and then came out on a branch to clean its whiskers and lounge in the setting sun. The camera GPS and this photo map says we were in Tanzania for this shot, but we must have been just on the border in the Masai Mara of Kenya, because we hadn't crossed the river into Tanzania yet. descr:
The black-headed weaver (Ploceus melanocephalus), also known as yellow-backed weaver, is a species of bird in the Ploceidae family.
The male Black-headed Weaver usually does the weaving, however, and the female sits for the eggs. The male stitches strips of straws to make a basket with a roof. He uses grasses to tie knots and make sure the nest is completely secure. Finally, he shows the nest to females, in effort to attract a mate. The males usually mate with many females during the mating season to get more offspring. They all nest in colonies, and in the end the females are left to raise their young alone. The seeds that the Black-headed Weaver tends to feed on are very common, so they do not need to stay and defend their family's territory or food.  

This beautiful male Black-headed Weaver was photographed on a late evening game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Red-eyed Weaver!

descr:
The Chestnut Sparrow (Passer eminibey) is a species of passerine bird in the sparrow family Passeridae. It is the smallest member of the sparrow family, at about 11 cm long. Like the other members of the sparrow family, the Chestnut Sparrow is a small, chunky songbird with a thick bill suited for its diet of seeds. 
The Chestnut sparrows are gregarious and are only occasionally found away from flocks. They frequently associate with queleas and other weavers. Adults feed on grass seeds, and those near human habitations will also eat crumbs and other household scraps. 
Chestnut Sparrow's likes dry savannah and is found in East Africa.

This very handsome male Chestnut Sparrow was photographed on a game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Handsome Chestnut!

descr:
The Kenya sparrow, also known as the Kenya rufous sparrow (Passer rufocinctus) is a sparrow found in Kenya and Tanzania. It tends to be found in dry wooded savannah and agricultural areas.
This is a common seed eater in Kenya highland farms, orchards, savanna and urban settings. They often forage on the soil for seeds as well as scraps of food dropped by people. Insects form a major part of the diet, particularly during nesting. Although there are many kinds of small brownish birds this one can be reasonably recognized by the rufous and gray head, the black throat patch, and the pale eyes. The female lacks extensive rufous (reddish brown) colour in the plumage, but retains the pale eyes.

The Beautiful Sparrow is a lifer and was photographed early in the morning on a game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya
title: The Kenyan Sparrow!

descr:
Just like a pet cat, a lion has a long tail which helps it to balance. Unlike any other cat, a lion’s tail has a black tassel at the end, which first appears when it is between five and seven months old. This can be used to lead other lions through long grass. Females raise their tail to give a 'follow me' signal to their cubs and also use it to communicate with each other when hunting prey. A lion’s tail also is a good sign of how it is feeling. By flicking its tail, a lion can warn others to stay away because it is in a bad mood. 
A lions tail length is 70 - 100 centimetres. Their tail ends in a hairy tuft. The tuft conceals a spine, approximately 5 millimetres long, formed of the final sections of tail bone fused together. 

The King is a member of the Sopa Pride and was seen sleeping on the rocks late in the evening during a game drive in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The King's Tail!

descr:
Cats are very territorial animals. They need to feel safe in their space and they need it to be clear to other cats that they are, in fact, the owner of that space. The best-known feline territory marking behaviour is urine spraying: Males and females,  can spray when they feel the need to plant “no trespassing” signs. 
Scent is used to identify members of the same colony, define territory, create familiarity, announce sexual readiness, learn more about unfamiliar cats in the environment, self-soothe, bond with another, or as a form of covert aggression.

This beautiful male Cheetah was seen spraying this tree with his urine on a early morning game drive in the Maasai Mara Game. Reserve, Kenya.

title: Sheep  -ish

descr:
The 5 boys on their second miss of the day. They had hunted a bit more typically of cheetah - jogging, stalking, getting closer, waiting. But they had picked targets (a small herd of wildebeests, maybe 20, none of which saw them approaching) while neglecting the fact that the wildebeests were in tall grass. Much too tall for a running cheetah - they could not see, and had to resort to popping up on the run (just like wild dogs). It was total chaos - and the cheetah looked clueless - typified by this image.

Cheetah (Acinonyx jubatus)

descr:
This was my last encounter with Malaika and her two sons Dogo and Kigumba. 
She was last seen on 4th March trying to cross the Olare Orok River, near the Double Cross area, never to be seen since. 
Malaika has been the Queen of countless visitors to the Maasai Mara as she wasn't shy of humans and would at times jump onto the roof of some safari vehicles. She was a very successful mother having raised five cubs who are now roaming in the savannah plains of Maasai Mara.  

Photographed on 23/07/2017.  during a game drive in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Last Encounter!

descr:
They were the reason we chose to go to the Mara. I do not really know how stable this 5 cheetah coalition is. When we were there we continued to see some squabbling among them. But while they are together, we expected to see some spectacular hunts as they go after "big" game like adult wildebeests and topis.

So, straight after we got into the safari vehicle, we were off to find them. Fortunately, they were in the park.

The Five Musketeers or the Fast Five

descr:
The Marico sunbird (Cinnyris mariquensis) is a species of bird in the Nectariniidae family. It is found in most of Southern Africa. 
The Marico Sunbird has a height of 11 cms and weighs around 11 gms. The head is coloured green while the bill is coloured black. It has a green coloured throat, black legs and a green coloured back. The eyes are brown.
This bird forages for food on the ground. They attack its prey aerially and feeds on wing or takes the prey to a secluded venue where it is killed, torn into small pieces and eaten.
This bird eats insects such as butterflies, bees, wasps, locusts and ants. These invertebrates are usually hawked aerially, killed and then eaten.
The bird also drinks nectar from flowers high up in the tree canopy.

This beautiful Marico sunbird is a lifer as this is the first ever photograph which was taken in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Multi-coloured Beauty!

descr:
The plains zebra (Equus quagga, formerly Equus burchellii), also known as the common zebra or Burchell's zebra, or locally as the "quagga" (not to be confused with the extinct subspecies), is the most common and geographically widespread species of zebra. It ranges from the south of Ethiopia through East Africa to as far south as Botswana and eastern South Africa. The plains zebra remains common in game reserves, but is threatened by human activities such as hunting for its meat and hide, as well as competition with livestock and encroachment by farming on much of its habitat.
The plains zebra is a highly social species, forming harems with a single stallion, several mares and their recent offspring; there are also bachelor groups. Groups may come together to form herds. The animals keep watch for predators rather than attempting to hide; they bark or snort when they see a predator, and the harem stallion attacks predators to defend his harem. 

This very handsome zebra foal was photographed following it's parents to the waterhole early in the morning in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: Handsome in Stripes!

descr:
The Chestnut Sparrow (Passer eminibey) is a species of passerine bird in the sparrow family Passeridae. It is the smallest member of the sparrow family, at about 11 cm long. The breeding male has deep chestnut plumage and the female and juvenile are coloured a duller grey with some chestnut markings. It is gregarious and found in arid areas ranging through the east of Africa from Darfur in Sudan to Tanzania, it is found in dry savanna, papyrus swamps, and near human habitation. 
The plumage of the breeding male is mostly a deep shade of chestnut in colour with black colouration on the face, wings, and tail. The breeding male is not easily confused with any other birds except the chestnut weaver, which is substantially larger and has white on its wings. 

This very handsome male Chestnut Sparrow is a lifer from me photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Chestnut Male!

descr:
Speke's weaver (Ploceus spekei) is a familiar East African songbird. Speke's weaver is found in northern and eastern Somalia, Ethiopia, Kenya (mostly the central highlands), and northeastern Tanzania. It inhabits savanna, bush, agricultural land, and towns. In parts of its range it is common, notably the densely populated area of Nairobi and environs, where it visits bird feeders.
The eyes are pale and the bill is on the large side for a weaver. Unlike many weavers, it has the same plumage all year. The adult male is yellow with black throat (edged rusty), face, and bill, and variable black mottling on the back. The adult female's upperparts are dull olive-gray with dusky brown streaks; the underparts are pale yellow, whiter on the belly and grayer on the flanks. The juvenile is similar but duller.
This species nests in colonies or occasionally singly. The nest, often woven in an acacia, is spherical with a short entrance tube opening sideways or downward. Many grass stems project sloppily, sometimes obscuring the shape. 

This handsome male Speke's Weaver was photographed early in the morning in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Handsome Weaver!

descr:
The three-banded plover, or three-banded sandplover (Charadrius tricollaris), is a small wader. This plover is resident in much of eastern and southern Africa and Madagascar, mainly on inland rivers, pools, and lakes. Its nest is a bare scrape on shingle. This species is often seen as single individuals, but it will form small flocks. It hunts by sight for insects, worms and other invertebrates. Three-banded plovers have a sharp whistled weeet-weet call.
The adult three-banded plover has medium brown upperparts, and the underparts are white except for the two black breast bands, separated by a white band, which give this species its common and scientific names. The head is strikingly patterned, with a black crown, white supercilia extending from the white forehead to meet on the back of the neck, and a grey face becoming brown on the neck. The eye ring and the base of the otherwise black bill are red.

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Tricollaris!

descr:
The Tawny Eagle (Aquila rapax) is a large bird of prey. Like all eagles, it belongs to the family Accipitridae. This is a large eagle, although it is one of the smaller species in the Aquila genus. It is 60 - 75 cm in length and has a wingspan of 159 - 190 cm. Weight can range from 1.6 to 3 kg. The Tawny Eagle has many colour variations, from a very light tan colour to a beautiful dark brown. 
Immature birds show less contrast than adults, but both show a range of variation in plumage colour.
It breeds in most of Africa both north and south of the Sahara Desert and across tropical southwestern Asia to India. The female eagle lays 1 – 3 eggs in a nest, and these hatch after being incubated for 39 – 45 days. As siblings can be aggressive towards each other, siblicide (killing of a sibling) is common in these species. Only the strongest of the chicks survive to adulthood.
Throughout its range, it favours open dry habitats such as desert, semidesert, steppes, or savannah plains.

This formidable Tawny Eagle was photographed late in the evening in Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Blue Sky Tawny!

descr:
The Wood Sandpiper (Tringa glareola) is a small wader. This Eurasian species is the smallest of the shanks, which are mid-sized long-legged waders of the family Scolopacidae. 
The wood sandpiper is a widespread migratory wading bird of Europe and Asia which overwinters in Africa.
The diet of the wood sandpiper varies seasonally, and includes invertebrates, small fish, frogs and plant matter.
Nesting is on the ground, the wood sandpiper usually lays three or four eggs.
The wood sandpiper can be seen in groups of up to 1,000 during migration.

This lovely Wood Sandpiper was photographed wading in the Talek River of Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.
title: The Sandpiper!

descr:
One of my favorite experiences on the African Safari was when our guides to took us in search of wildlife after sundown. I had a very specific image in mind — a giraffe under the glow of the milky way — but the moon was right in its path, making it a difficult shot. Our spotter eventually identified three giraffes sitting peacefully under the stars. I took a few test shots at different shutter speeds and was able to peg a good exposure at six seconds. Thankfully, the giraffes weren't in a hurry. I was able to compose this panorama with 14 total images, seven on top and seven below. Shot at 4000 ISO at f/2.8, 70mm.

#MaasaiMara #Kenya #AfricanSafari #Giraffe #Nikon

descr:
The three-banded plover, or three-banded sandplover (Charadrius tricollaris), is a small wader. This plover is resident in much of eastern and southern Africa and Madagascar, mainly on inland rivers, pools, and lakes. Its nest is a bare scrape on shingle. This species is often seen as single individuals, but it will form small flocks. It hunts by sight for insects, worms and other invertebrates. These  plovers have a sharp whistled weeet-weet call.

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.

descr: This young male elephant bears the scars and pain of man's greed. He was probably ensnared (far front foot), then shot at, the gunman aiming for his heart, but missing (near front leg). His injury was deep and septic, He couldn't walk very well and was alone, which is unusual for an elephant of his age. What could we do? I told our guide we had a GPS and we gave the coordinates to the Kenyan Wildlife. Did they find him? Did he survive? I don't know, but I do know we should be pressuring the market that creates this demand to STOP KILLING ELEPHANTS!
title: He escaped with his life, hopefully...

descr: This baby zebra was completely alone - his mother was no where in sight. The foal lay under the shade of the tree but sadly we frightened him and he ran towards the wildebeest for safety. Wrong move! They started attacking him by butting and kicking out at him. Confused he ran towards another group of wildebeest, but they did the same and wouldn't let him back under the shade of the tree. It was midday, it was very hot and he was alone. To cut a long story short, we had lunch then came back to see if he was still there. There was no lone foal but there was a foal the same size as him with it's mother. We are hoping it's same one.

descr: The  Loita migration of White-bearded Wildebeest (Connochaetes taurinus). These are the ones "left behind". Rather than go for the full migration out of the Masai Mara and around the Serengeti, quite a few Wildebeest choose to migrate around the Masai Mara looking for sweet grass. This smaller migration is the Loita migration.
title: White Bearded Wildebeest on the Plains

descr:
CAESAR, a large male lion found between Lookout and the Ol Keju Ronkai river, chasing the cubs in the 9 pride. (This is what a fully grown male lion looks like when at full speed and shot at 1/1000th). The 9 had killed a young buffalo and were towards the end of their meal when over the hill came Caesar; who charged the feast - stealing it - and chasing the 4 1-2 year old and 2 much younger cubs, while the 3 adult lionesses blocked and distracted him. Caesar is far to large to succeed in catching cubs of these ages if they are aware of him - as they were. While running about he began calling his brother Notch II, who also came over the hill after about 10 minutes. Notch II went straight to the feast. Both Caesar and Notch II are sons of Notch -- the most famous lion in the Masai Mara region

This is the final processed version for now and optimised for web viewing.
title: 20170315-08-14-0520170315-0814_D507131 close cropped with WEB SIZED SRGB

descr: Best shots of this trip to the Masai Mara - Meet Loran, a very productive female leopard -- mother to Luluka (who left her last year) and now a new cub. Loran is to be found way up the Narrow River (Ol Keju Ronkai) and here daughter was further down towards the Mara River. This shot was taken in the early morning as Loran suns/warms herself on a mound near the River and her den before heading off to her den to sleep with her cub. Loran sits with her back to the rising sun, which is good for her; but makes shots along her body more challenging. Now heading of to sleep - but taking the time to check around for prey and predators and having a yawn. We were able to get below her eye-line and this makes for a great opportunity.  This is the final processed version for now and optimised for web viewing.
title: 20170306-08-11-53_D502764 with WEB SIZED SRGB

descr: One of my best --Loki in the early morning -- Loki is one of the 4 blond Vikings who invaded Long-face's pride from the south and drove Long-face away. He has a wound above his left eye, which we assume was as a result of an encounter with one of the lionesses in Long-faces former pride. Perhaps the best shot (and one of the first) I took of Loki in this early morning light. 35 minutes after sunrise, with the low light along the body and nice light fall off on the left side of his face - shot was taken spot metered. Loki looks evil/fearce and I was glad we were 30m away. I had to dodge and burn a little to even out the tones and reduce the white-levels on the sun side of the face and right shoulder. This is the final version, with a slightly reduced saturation.
title: 20170306-07-20-03_D502605 WM

descr: Loki in the early morning -- Loki is one of the 4 blond Vikings who invaded Long-face's pride from the south and drove Long-face away. This shot - directly into the sun was an attempt for something different and to catch rim light through the mane. It was shot Spot Metered without EV / exposure compensation. descr: Best shots of this trip to the Masai Mara - Luluka, the 2-3 year old daughter of Loran, is fending for herself in territory close to her mother near the Ol Keju Ronkai (Narrow) River in the Masai Mara NR, Kenya. We spotted Luluka standing very still in tall grass and all of a sudden she pounced on a large male adult Reedbuck and after some struggling she made her kill. We had no idea that the Reedbuck was hiding in the tall grass, but Luluka did. After a brief rest she proceeded to drag her kill 200-300m to a nearby ditch, where she would remove the innards and have a quick feast before dragging the kill another 100m or so to a large tree next to the river. She would then climb the tree carrying this large animal 2-3 times her weight and store it safely on a branch up the tree. None of these shots have been photoshopped to remove errant grass or the effects of grass between the camera and the subject -- I will decide later what looks better.
title: 20170319-08-10-09_D509616 WM

We spotted Luluka standing very still in tall wet grass and all of a sudden she pounced on a large male adult Reedbuck and after some struggling she made her kill. We had no idea that the Reedbuck was hiding in the tall grass, but Luluka did. After a brief rest she proceeded to drag her kill 200-300m to a nearby ditch, where she would remove the innards and have a quick feast before dragging the kill another 100m or so to a large tree next to the river. She would then climb the tree carrying this large animal 2-3 times her weight and store it safely on a branch up the tree. None of these shots have been photoshopped to remove errant grass or the effects of grass between the camera and the subject -- I will decide later what looks better.

descr: Meet Shambi, during a rain storm in the Masai Mara. Shambi was with Samir/Box-Nose, the two lions who shortly before this stole a buffalo kill from two younger male lions. Male lions are roaming more and more widely as the level of available food drops. With the dry season ending, predators in the Masai Mara NR face a hard time until July when the big herds migrate again into the reserve. Fights over food, territory and females become increasingly common at this time of year. Many other shots of Shambi, his partner in crime Samir/Box-nose, and the other predators and pray of the Masai Mara NR, Kenya, from my current trip can be seen in the album flic.kr/s/aHskVyQzEc and soon in high def on my website www.andymillerphoto.co.uk/.

descr: Notch II get straight down to feasting in the Masai Mara NR Lookout area. Caesar, his brother, was being marked/blocked by the 3 lionesses of Long-face's former pride, who together with 6 cubs ("the 9") ran away when the four Vikings drove Long-face off. The 9 are seemingly thriving even though they have no male to fight for them. They had killed and largely eaten a buffalo, before Caesar came over the hill, stealing the rest of the meal and chasing the cubs. Notch II (who looks most like his father Notch) is one of five famous brothers, including Long-face, whose pride the 9 was.
title: 20170315-08-41-48_D507360

descr:
The common hippopotamus (Hippopotamus amphibius), or hippo, is a large, mostly herbivorous mammal in sub-Saharan Africa. The name comes from the ancient Greek for "river horse". 

Common hippos are recognisable by their barrel-shaped torsos, wide-opening mouths revealing large canine tusks, nearly hairless bodies, columnar-like legs and large size; adults average 1,500 kg (males) and 1,300 kg (females), making them the largest species of land mammal after the elephants and the white and Indian rhinoceros. Despite its stocky shape and short legs, it is capable of running 30 km/h over short distances. The hippopotamus is a highly aggressive and unpredictable animal and is ranked among the most dangerous animals in Africa. Nevertheless, they are still threatened by habitat loss and poaching for their meat and ivory canine teeth.

Photographed in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve, Kenya.

descr: Meet Loran, a very productive female leopard -- mother to Luluka (who left her last year) and now a new cub. Loran is to be found way up the Narrow River (Ol Keju Ronkai) and her daughter was further down towards the Mara River. This shot was taken in the early morning as Loran suns/warms herself on a mound near the River and her den before heading off to her den to sleep with her cub. Loran sits with her back to the rising sun, which is good for her; but makes shots along her body more challenging. Now heading of to sleep - but taking the time to check around for prey and predators. Here she turned into the sun and the results are great. The sun is very bright and so Loran is squinting as she looks about. We were able to get below her eye-line and this makes for a great opportunity.
title: 20170306-08-17-26_D502794

Now heading of to sleep - but taking the time to check around for prey and predators. Here she turned into the sun and the results are great. The sun is very bright and so Loran is squinting as she looks about. We were able to get below her eye-line and this makes for a great opportunity.

descr: Loki in the early morning -- Loki is one of the 4 blond Vikings who invaded Long-face's pride from the south and drove Long-face away. He has a wound above his left eye, which we assume was as a result of an encounter with one of the lionesses in Long-faces former pride. Perhaps the best shot (and one of the first) I took of Loki in this early morning light. 35 minutes after sunrise, with the low light along the body and nice light fall off on the left side of his face - shot was taken spot metered. Loki looks evil/fearce and I was glad we were 30m away. I had to dodge and burn a little to even out the tones and reduce the white-levels on the sun side of the face and right shoulder. I have added the final version into this album as well.

descr: These two sub-adult females and their brother were very interested in a wilderbeest mother and baby. The male went towards them, whilst the girls stayed behind. We didn't think they'd actually hunt but the male gained speed and then the females decided to join in. It was a very haphazard affair, with no organisation and both the wilderbeest mother and baby got away in a cloud of dust! I'm sure it won't be long before they are killing machines.
title: Young, but ready to hunt

descr:

descr:
We spotted the Spotted hyena (Crocuta crocuta) chewing on a small chunk of something, not far from where we had seen lions (Panthera leo) earlier in the day. We suspected this was stolen merchandise, and the cracking of bones could be heard as it chewed. We figured something was going to happen, as it was near sundown, and the lions would be waking up. And sure enough, it did. This lioness was despatched by the pride for the task. Although well fed, it still wanted that chunk back.
Sighted from -1.206250, 35.16316 (01°12'22.50"S 035°09'47.38"E)

descr:
We visited a traditional Maasai village during a trip to the Mara North Conservancy, in which we were fortunate enough to experience Maasai culture, song a dance.

We were also fortunate enough to be able to photograph the Maasai people, and this is one of the young women who performed for us during our visit.
title: Portrait of a Young Maasai Woman
