descr:
When we visited the Maasai Mara region of south-western Kenya, on one day we decided to depart the Mara North Conservancy in a southward direction, where we entered the Maasai Mara National Reserve, which extends to the border of Kenya and Tanzania.

It was in the National Reserve that we had our very first sighting of cheetahs in Africa, and here in this image, this cheetah, along with the other four members of that cheetah family, was heading in the direction of some plains game which may have been the next meal.

This cheetah is out on the open plains, where a cheetah feels comfortable in spite of ever-present danger, but where a leopard would seldom be seen.
title: Cheetah on the Move

descr:
On our fifth day in the Maasai Mara, we decided to head south from the Mara North Conservancy, and into the public Maasai Mara National Reserve.

Our first exciting sighting in the main reserve was the Double Crossing Pride, which had congregated around a deceased elephant.

As we understand, the elephant was not killed by the lions, but it certainly was providing them with a meal.

It wasn't just the lions who wanted a feast.  More and more hyenas had also congregated nearby, and their behaviour and vocalisations were becoming increasingly aggressive.

The lions weren't happy, and were roaring and hissing at the hyenas, who were becoming closer to mounting an attack.

In this image, one of the Double Crossing Pride females exposes her teeth in anger at a nearby pack of hyenas, as she spits at them in no uncertain terms to warn them to stay away.
title: Stay Away

descr:
During a day out in the Maasai Mara National Reserve, we were fortunate enough to encounter cheetahs.

The mother and her four sub-adult cubs were making their way towards us, and beyond, as they followed some distant antelope.

In this image, two of the cheetahs are scouting, looking for what might be their next meal.
title: Scouting

descr:
On our ninth game drive in the Maasai Mara, we headed out of the Mara North Conservancy, and into the Maasai Mara National Reserve.

Here, for the first time, we spotted and photographed cheetahs: a mother and four cubs.

Unlike leopards, cheetahs are happy to be out in the open, and for quite a while, we watched, photographed and followed them as they started to slowly but surely pursue antelopes for a future meal.

Here, during one of the periods during which the cheetahs stopped moving, I photographed one looking straight at us.

It was fantastic to see cheetahs for the first time, and as it would turn out, we got to see all three species of African big cats (cheetahs, leopards and lions) in the same day.
title: Spotted by a Cheetah

descr: This is long curved beak is perfectly suited to get nectar from these long skinny flowers. The flowers dont belong to the Acacia tree that is the substrate for this flowering semi-parasitic vine of the genus Phragmanthera. The male was in the same tree but would never venture far enough out of the cover for a shot worth posting.
title: Female Amethyst Sunbird - Enelerai, Kenya

descr: On my last evening in Kenya, I was walking at sunset and got a great picture of this Barbet in the golden hour. It was relatively good with my presence and stay for some time in the top of the tree. The area that we stayed in was dry shrub or Miambo.
title: Red-fronted Barbet - Enelerai, Kenya

descr: This group of behemoths were relaxing in the deepest part of the Mara River. There were close to 70 animals that I could see. There wasn't much movement when we showed up but occasionally a Hippo would move or submerge. These guys had made tracks out of the river well up the hill to where they graze at night and you would not believe the small trail that this very large animal leaves. The path is very distinct and it is only a food in width.
title: Hippopatomus Herd - Masai Mara, Kenya

descr: This yellow finch was perched up on a Candelabra Tree in the early morning sunlight. The finches in the area are strikingly similar and is tough to identify them unless you get a bit of time to look for the differences. At least for a visiting birder. These birds remind me of the Pine Siskins at home.
title: African Citril - Enelarai, Kenya

descr: Certainly lived up to its name here in Kenya at least. I think I saw this species in every location except in the grasslands. Great voice on these birds as they would generally be singing when not looking for food. This was on one of the fence posts for the camp we were staying in.
title: Common Bulbul - Enelerai, Kenya

descr: This Embrezid was snooping around the front of the mess tent in the shade. It is a tad more colorful than the sparrows we get here on the West Coast. This was taken while on Voluntour with Free the Children.
title: Golden-breasted Bunting - Enelerai, Kenya

descr: The sunbirds were thick on the Sisal plants. This gorgeous bird was there with at least 4 other species of sunbirds and many other species, including weavers, bulbuls and starlings. Each plant would sometimes have 15 birds moving back and forth between the pads of flowers.
title: Scarlet-chested Sunbird - Enelerai, Kenya

descr: The Sisal plants were a huge hit with a good deal of birds. If they weren't cover for some of the skulkers, they were a lofty perch and finally a feast for the nectar feeders. This Starling was one of a pair that were feeding on the blooms along with the weavers and sunbirds. Had there been a way to get to that height in a blind, I could have stayed there for at least a couple days taking photos.
title: Greater Blue-eared Glossy-starling - Enelerai, Narok, Kenya

descr: These guys are great to watch. Half the time they are upside down or hanging off of the branches instead of sitting on them. Sometimes they 4 of them will sit on the very same spot and you cant tell where one bird begins and the other ends. This was a family group of 8 or nine birds. I could never get a good count as they would make their way between shrubs one or two at a time.
title: Speckled Mousebird - Enelarai, Narok, Kenya

descr: There were several types of Canaries stopping in, mostly in pairs. This bird was alone and was taking reprieve from the wind which seemed to be non stop here. The white belly is hard to discern from some angles, but here it is pretty clear.
title: White-bellied Canary - Enelarai, Kenya

descr: This is one of the more colorful birds that inhabited the area. There were several pairs of these beauties roaming the area. The females were not quite as bold, but could certainly still win a beauty contest. Most of the time these birds were moving along the ground looking for seeds and grasses and would flush to the nearest bush for cover when they felt it necessary.
title: Purple Grenadier - Enelelai, Kenya

descr: A pair of Ring-necked Doves visited camp on a regular occasion and sat in the flowering Sisal plant. The coos of the doves are very relaxing.
title: Ring-necked Dove - Enelerai, Kenya

descr: Had some time trying to get this one fully in front of the camera as he was always skulking about the camp, with its mate. It had very low clicks, bongs and whistles that would be answered from a nearby bush. The habitat was Miambo brush and with partial cleared and cultivated area all on a steep hill. Always skulking but making lots of noise.
title: Slate-colored Boubou - Enelerai, Narok, Kenya

descr: This photo was taken in the Me to We camp in the Enelarai community. The male would sometimes make his way from the shade to the flowering sisal plant, puff out his chest and call to the females in the nearby trees
title: Laughing Dove - Enelerai, Kenya

title: mm0025

descr:
Or hard yakka - as the Aussies would say, being an oxpecker on the rump side of the world
Sighted from -1.26186,34.99558 (01°15'42.7"S 034°59'44.1"E)
1 Sep 2013  4:50pm
3D4_6154
Nikkor 400/2.8 VR

I had named them Red-billed Oxpeckers (Buphagus erythrorhynchus), but they are in fact  Yellow-billed Oxpeckers (Buphagus africanus) on a Common eland (Taurotragus oryx). In the Red-Billed, their entire bill is red.

descr: Several trips to Africa previously had not rewarded me with any true sightings of the beautiful leopard. This trip I was determined would be different. A vigil each dusk often returned no results. Determined that my patience would be rewarded, I joined a group on a four hour 'stakeout' to capture a glimpse of this most elusive creature. Scanning undergrowth and craning necks towards the branches of leopard friendly trees, we saw nothing. Nothing! Then we turned a corner on our route homeward and there she was, seemingly waiting for us. Watching. Motionless. I stole this opportunity to make a lifelong dream come true and capture the moment I had always dreamed of - me..eye to eye with a leopard.

descr: Driving into Masai Mara through the Ololoolo Gate in the Mara Triangle just after sunrise on Christmas Day, we were lucky to see this African White-backed Vulture sitting on a huge boulder on the roadside. It was busy scanning the horizon for any activity within the vicinity. They are known to have terrific sight and can spot a carcass from over 5 Kilometres away. Wikipedia says: The White-backed Vulture (Gyps africanus) is an Old World vulture in the family Accipitridae, which also includes eagles, kites, buzzards and hawks. It is closely related to the European Griffon Vulture, G. fulvus. Sometimes it is called African White-backed Vulture to distinguish it from the Oriental White-backed Vulture—nowadays usually called Indian White-rumped Vulture—to which it was formerly believed to be closely related. The White-backed Vulture is a typical vulture, with only down feathers on the head and neck, very broad wings and short tail feathers. It has a white neck ruff. The adult’s whitish back contrasts with the otherwise dark plumage. Juveniles are largely dark. This is a medium-sized vulture; its body mass is 4.2 to 7.2 kilograms (9.3–16 lb), it is 78 to 98 cm (31 to 39 in) long and has a 1.96 to 2.25 m (6 to 7 ft) wingspan. Like other vultures it is a scavenger, feeding mostly from carcasses of animals which it finds by soaring over savannah. It also takes scraps from human habitations. It often moves in flocks. It breeds in trees on the savannah of west and east Africa, laying one egg. The population is mostly resident. As it is rarer than previously believed, its conservation status was reassessed from Least Concern to Near Threatened in the 2007 IUCN Red List. In 2012 it was further uplisted to Endangered. descr:
Dit is echt bewust spelen met witbalans. We waren deze cheetah al een tijdje aan het volgen en het werd al schemerig alleen was het erg bewolkt en bij lange na geen 'mooie rode' zonsondergang.
Omdat ik wel wist dat ik met witbalans er behoorlijk rood in kon draaien ben ik een witbalans trappetje gaan schieten naar het uiterste. Zo is deze foto's gemaakt met 10.000 Kelvin. Ik weet dat ik voor de sluitertijd de ISO eerst naar beneden had moeten halen maar vanwege de schemering stond hij daar nog op en ook in dit geval een 'spugende lama' actie dus daar even niet bij stilgestaan. 
En helaas had de Cheetah geen geduld om rustig te blijven zitten en is de foto dan ook wat bewogen, erg jammer. Maar we hebben nu wel een prachtig silhouet van dit mooie beest in onze verzameling.

descr:
During my recent trip to Masai Mara, I managed to see the famous Marsh Pride. This is one of the four Male Lions from the Marsh Pride who became famous when they ousted the Notch males and killed 17 cubs in the process. 
For those on Facebook and follow the BIGCATFANZ will know that all the Lions in the area have been identified and given names. The four males of the Marsh pride include Sikio (pictured above) Scarface, Morani and Hunter. 
It was a real pleasure watching the young females from the Marsh pride trying to get Sikio's attention for mating!

descr: One of the unexpected highlights of my trip to Mara Bushtops in Africa was the people and the culture. I hadn really thought about it much before I got there, as all I had on my mind was epic night skies and amazing wildlife. But as soon as I touched down in the Mara, I was greeted by the Masai (Maasai) people, and then interacted with them every day during my time there. I was assigned a Masai Warrior for my security and as a spotter, and he even helped me with all my camera equipment that I would bring along for the game drives and photo missions. I also got to visit a traditional Masai Enkang and was invited into one of the huts within the Enkang. I was offered cows milk and blood to drink, which I politely declined, but it was incredible to see how the Masai live even today without all of the mod-cons the western world take for granted - in fact the Masai gauge their wealth by the amount of cattle they have, and I was told that if you were to offer them either a Ferrari car or cattle, they would definitely take the cattle. In this photo, one of the Masai pose outside a traditional hut under the night sky with the Milky Way over head complete with shooting star! The huts are traditionally constructed by the women and are made with timber poles interwoven with a lattice of smaller branches, and then plastered with a mixture of sticks, grass, cow dung and ash which bakes hard in the hot sun. descr: Vist to the Maji Moto Maasai Community Project (majimoto.org). The organisation works to maintain cultural values, ceremonies and traditions amongst the Maasai, while striving to eliminate harmful practices such as female circumcision, early marriage, and lack of education. Income is generated by a comprehensive programme of adventures from our short visit to week long safaris and cultural experiences.

descr: Maji Moto Maasai Widows Project. In the Maasai culture, young women are often married to older men, increasing the likelihood of being widowed. In this culture women do not have a right to own (or inherit) any property, and teenage widows with children are often left behind when a husband dies, leaving them with no home or means to live. In 2007 a widows' village was established where the women can live peacefully in the companionship of others and find ways to work. They currently earn income by caring for livestock, performing traditional songs & dances for visitors, making and selling beadwork and running a solar cell phone charging business.

descr:
Traditional Maasai lifestyle centres around their cattle which constitute their primary source of food. The measure of a man's wealth is in terms of cattle and children. A herd of 50 cattle is respectable, and the more children the better. A man who has plenty of one but not the other is considered to be poor

We bezochten een Masai dorp, van 124 inwoners. We brachten eten en spulletjes voor hun school mee. Wij kregen zang , dans en een rondleiding. Veel kinderen en bijna geen mensen tussen de 30 en 40. De kleine kinderen willen allemaal hand in hand met je lopen. Het zijn schatjes!

descr: Our cruiser, courtesy of the Sarova Mara resort located in the heart of the Maasi Mara National Reserve, Kenya.  These 4-wheel drive vehicles are a must as the terrain in the reserve consists primarily of dirt/gravel roads.  Note the absence of glass in the doors of the vehicle.  More on that later...
title: LandCruiser - Keekorok Airstrip

descr:
SafariLink is the airline we used to fly from Wilson Airport in Nairobi to the Keekorok dirt airstrip.  Keekorok Airport (IATA:HKKE) is located in Maasai Mara, in Trans Mara District, Rift Valley Province, in the southwestern part of Kenya on the map, close to the International border with the Republic of Tanzania, near the location called Keekorok.

As we disembarked and collected our gear, our Maasi guide Antony was there waiting to take us on our first game drive.
